Docker Swarm Auto-Scaling in Production
Objectives
Design and deploy a multi-service Docker Swarm stack with overlay networking, health checks, and constraint-based placement policies
Implement a metrics-driven autoscaler that reads live container statistics and issues scaling decisions against the Swarm API
Validate scaling behavior under synthetic load and perform a zero-downtime rolling update while the autoscaler is active
Prerequisites
Comfort with Linux process management, file permissions, and shell scripting on Ubuntu
Familiarity with HTTP request/response cycles and TCP port binding
Understanding of containerization concepts: images, layers, namespaces, and cgroups
Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Environment Setup and Verification
Step 1.1: Install Docker Engine and supporting CLI tools
Your instance has no container runtime. Install Docker Engine from the official repository, then install jq (a JSON processor used to parse Docker API output) and apache2-utils (which provides ab, the Apache HTTP benchmarking tool used in Task 3).

sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg lsb-release jq apache2-utils

sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings

curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
If the gpg command fails, the official installation guide is at: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/

sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list <<'EOF'
deb [arch=amd64 signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu jammy stable
EOF

sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-buildx-plugin docker-compose-plugin
Troubleshoot this step:

You may see: E: Malformed entry 1 in list file /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list â this means the heredoc wrote a broken line.
Inspect the file with cat /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list â it must be one unbroken line; delete it with sudo rm /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list and recreate using the heredoc above.
Official reference: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
newgrp docker
docker version
docker compose version
jq --version
ab -V
You should see Docker Engine version output, Compose version output, a jq version string, and the ab version line. If any command returns command not found, the corresponding package did not install correctly.

Step 1.2: Initialize Docker Swarm and verify cluster state
Docker Swarm is Docker's native clustering mode. A Swarm consists of manager nodes (which schedule work) and worker nodes (which run containers). In this single-node lab the manager also acts as a worker.

PRIVATE_IP=$(hostname -I | awk '{print $1}')
docker swarm init --advertise-addr "$PRIVATE_IP"
docker node ls
docker info --format '{{.Swarm.LocalNodeState}}'
The docker node ls output must show exactly one node with STATUS=Ready, AVAILABILITY=Active, and MANAGER STATUS=Leader. The docker info command must print active.

Troubleshoot this step:

You may see: Error response from daemon: must specify a listening address because the address to advertise is not recognized as a system address â this means hostname -I returned an unexpected value.
Run ip addr show to find the correct interface IP and pass it explicitly: docker swarm init --advertise-addr <your-ip>.
Official reference: https://docs.docker.com/engine/swarm/swarm-tutorial/create-swarm/
Task 2: Build and Deploy a Scalable Service Stack
Step 2.1: Build a containerized web service with a structured health endpoint
Design a Node.js (or Python Flask) HTTP service that satisfies all of the following constraints:

Exposes GET / returning JSON with at minimum the fields hostname, version, and replica_id
Exposes GET /health returning {"status": "ok"} with HTTP 200; this endpoint must respond within 200 ms under no load
Exposes GET /stress that performs CPU-bound work for exactly 800 ms before responding, used to drive autoscaler decisions in Task 3
The image must be built locally and tagged swarm-app:v1; it must not pull from a public registry at runtime
Your Dockerfile must include a HEALTHCHECK instruction that calls /health every 20 seconds with a 5-second timeout and 2 retries before marking the container unhealthy.

The service interface contract is:

interface HealthResponse {
  status: "ok" | "degraded";
  hostname: string;
  uptime_seconds: number;
}

interface RootResponse {
  hostname: string;
  version: string;
  replica_id: string;
  timestamp: string;
}

interface StressResponse {
  hostname: string;
  duration_ms: number;
  completed: boolean;
}
Confirm the image builds without error and that docker run --rm -p 3000:3000 swarm-app:v1 responds correctly to curl -s http://localhost:3000/health before proceeding.

Step 2.2: Deploy a Swarm stack with placement constraints and resource limits
A Swarm stack (defined in a Compose file with version: "3.8" or higher) allows you to declare services, networks, and deployment policies as a single unit. Deploy a stack named prod that satisfies all of the following constraints:

The web service runs swarm-app:v1 with an initial replica count of 2
Each replica is constrained to at most 0.5 CPU and 128 MB of memory via resources.limits
The service publishes port 8080 on the host using ingress mode (Docker Swarm's built-in load balancer that distributes requests across all replicas)
All services communicate over a dedicated overlay network named prod-net with attachable: true
The rolling update policy sets parallelism: 1, delay: 15s, and failure_action: rollback
docker stack deploy -c docker-compose.yml prod
docker stack services prod
docker service ps prod_web
Confirm that docker stack services prod shows 2/2 replicas running and that curl -s http://localhost:8080/health returns {"status":"ok"} before proceeding.

Task 3: Implement a Metrics-Driven Autoscaler and Validate Under Load
Step 3.1: Implement a polling autoscaler as a long-running shell process
The autoscaler is a shell script that runs as a background process on the manager node. It must satisfy all of the following behavioral contracts:

Poll docker stats --no-stream --format json every 15 seconds to collect aggregate CPU percentage across all running tasks of prod_web
Compute the mean CPU percentage across all sampled containers; if the mean exceeds 60%, issue a scale-up by one replica (up to a hard maximum of 8); if the mean falls below 15% for two consecutive polling cycles, issue a scale-down by one replica (down to a hard minimum of 2)
Write every decision (timestamp, mean CPU, current replicas, action taken) as a single JSON line to ~/autoscaler.log so decisions can be audited
Never issue more than one scaling command per polling cycle; after issuing a scale command, skip the next polling cycle entirely to allow Swarm to converge before re-evaluating
The autoscaler interface contract is:

# autoscaler.sh
# Required environment variables (must be set before running):
#   SERVICE_NAME   â fully qualified Swarm service name (e.g. prod_web)
#   MIN_REPLICAS   â integer lower bound
#   MAX_REPLICAS   â integer upper bound
#   CPU_HIGH       â scale-up threshold as integer percentage (e.g. 60)
#   CPU_LOW        â scale-down threshold as integer percentage (e.g. 15)
#   POLL_INTERVAL  â seconds between polls (e.g. 15)
#   LOG_FILE       â absolute path to the JSONL audit log

# Exit codes:
#   0 â clean shutdown via SIGTERM
#   1 â SERVICE_NAME not found in Swarm at startup
Run the autoscaler in the background before starting the load test:

export SERVICE_NAME=prod_web MIN_REPLICAS=2 MAX_REPLICAS=8 \
       CPU_HIGH=60 CPU_LOW=15 POLL_INTERVAL=15 \
       LOG_FILE=~/autoscaler.log
bash autoscaler.sh &
AUTOSCALER_PID=$!
echo "Autoscaler PID: $AUTOSCALER_PID"
Confirm the log file exists and contains at least one JSON line before proceeding:

sleep 20
cat ~/autoscaler.log
Step 3.2: Drive scaling events with synthetic load and perform a rolling update
Generate enough HTTP load to push mean container CPU above the 60% threshold, observe the autoscaler scale up, then perform a zero-downtime rolling update to swarm-app:v2 while load is still running.

Phase A â Generate load:

ab -n 50000 -c 40 -k http://localhost:8080/stress &
LOAD_PID=$!
While load runs, watch replica count change in real time:

watch -n 5 'docker service ls --filter name=prod_web --format "table {{.Name}}\t{{.Replicas}}" && echo "" && tail -5 ~/autoscaler.log | jq .'
You must observe at least one scale-up event in ~/autoscaler.log before proceeding to Phase B.

Phase B â Rolling update under load:

Build swarm-app:v2 by modifying the version field in your application's root response to "v2" and rebuilding the image. Then issue the update:

docker build -t swarm-app:v2 .
docker service update \
  --image swarm-app:v2 \
  --update-parallelism 1 \
  --update-delay 15s \
  --update-order start-first \
  prod_web
Monitor the update convergence:

docker service ps prod_web --format "table {{.Name}}\t{{.Image}}\t{{.CurrentState}}\t{{.DesiredState}}"
Phase C â Stop load and observe scale-down:

kill $LOAD_PID
Wait at least two polling cycles (30 seconds) and confirm the autoscaler logs a scale-down event and replica count returns toward the minimum.

Phase D â Stop autoscaler and clean up:

kill $AUTOSCALER_PID
docker stack rm prod
docker network rm prod-net 2>/dev/null || true
docker swarm leave --force
docker image rm swarm-app:v1 swarm-app:v2 2>/dev/null || true
Confirm docker node ls returns an error indicating Swarm is no longer active.

Code Contracts
// Autoscaler decision record â each line written to LOG_FILE must conform to this shape
interface ScalerDecision {
  timestamp: string;          // ISO 8601
  mean_cpu_pct: number;       // 0â100, two decimal places
  current_replicas: number;
  action: "scale_up" | "scale_down" | "no_action" | "cooldown_skip";
  new_replicas: number | null; // null when action is no_action or cooldown_skip
}
# docker stats output format string used by the autoscaler
# Students must parse this output; the format flag controls which fields are emitted
docker stats --no-stream --format '{"name":"{{.Name}}","cpu":"{{.CPUPerc}}"}'
Expected Outcomes
~/autoscaler.log contains a chronological sequence of ScalerDecision JSON lines showing at least one scale_up event during load and at least one scale_down event after load stops
docker service ps prod_web (captured before cleanup) shows tasks running swarm-app:v2 with no tasks in Failed state, confirming the rolling update completed without dropping the service
Troubleshooting
If the autoscaler never triggers a scale-up despite load running, what does the raw output of docker stats --no-stream show for the prod_web tasks, and does the CPU percentage reflect work on the /stress endpoint or on a different endpoint â and what would explain the discrepancy?

If the rolling update stalls with tasks stuck in Preparing state, what does docker service ps prod_web --no-trunc reveal about the failure reason, and how would you determine whether the issue is an image pull failure, a health check timeout, or a resource limit violation?

Conclusion
This lab demonstrated how Docker Swarm's scheduling primitives â overlay networks, ingress load balancing, resource limits, and rolling update policies â compose into a production-grade deployment model. The custom autoscaler exposed the gap between Swarm's declarative API and the reactive control logic that production systems require, which purpose-built orchestrators like Kubernetes address natively. The rolling update exercise under live load confirmed that start-first ordering and health-check gating are the minimum requirements for zero-downtime deployments in any replicated service architecture.
